Tasveer was formed after 9/11, in March 2002, to amend the misrepresentations of the the South Asians in the media. 

The mission of Tasveer is to cultivate a safe, non-judgemental space for our community members in which we can critically engage in matters relating to South Asia and the Diaspora of its people. 

We started out holding small screenings showing documentaries and films on the the identity of the South Asians.
Since our first screening held on the occasion of Gay Pride, we have conducted over 200 programs. While South Asian communities are very diverse, with people hailing from numerous countries and representing many cultural experiences, languages and religions, many issues are commonly stigmatized in our communities and are not publicly discussed. Much of Tasveer’s programming has been focused on bringing light to these often difficult issues, empowering artists to tell their stories and audiences to engage in conversations. Some of these activities have included: 
-a first-ever South Asian LGBTQ Film Festival, which was presented in addition to the South Asian LGBTQ films that are regularly programmed into our Annual South Asian Film Festival; 
-a talk by an activist/writer about domestic violence and dowry laws in India; 
-a film screening fundraiser to benefit HIV/AIDS work in India; 
-sponsorship of South Asian films in the Seattle Human Rights Film Festival;
-sponsorship of Indian Gay Lesbian Festival called Kashik:
-organizing anti-homophobia workshop in the community;
-films and panel discussions marking the 20th and 25th anniversaries of the Bhopal disaster; and
